        <title>Reading and Reflection</title>
        <contents>&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reading and Reflection on CCRS for Administrators&lt;/strong&gt;: While this module is not focused on the CCRS, it is important that administrators (and teachers) see the connections.  This module can give you a head start with thinking about CCRS implementation in adult ESL. To learn more about the rationale for the CCRS in adult in education, read the introduction (pages 1-11) to&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a target="_blank" title="Open College and Career Readiness Standards for Adult Education" href="http://lincs.ed.gov/professional-development/resource-collections/profile-521"&gt;&lt;em&gt;College and Career Readiness Standards for Adult Education&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span style="color: #000000;"&gt;(Pimentel, 2013) and think about these questions as you read.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000; font-size: medium;"&gt;1. Where is your  state currently with regard to the integration of college or career readiness competencies in adult ESL programming, regardless of whether you have begun implementing CCRS?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000; font-size: medium;"&gt;2. What have learned from this document that will help you make the case for increased rigor in adult ESL when working with teachers in your program or state?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
